==Negative arguments==

In general, the arguments x, y, z of Carlson&#x27;s integrals may not be real and negative, as this would place a branch point on the path of integration, making the integral ambiguous. However, if the second argument of formula_6, or the fourth argument, p, of formula_9 is negative, then this results in a simple pole on the path of integration. In these cases the Cauchy principal value (finite part) of the integrals may be of interest; these are

:formula_99

and

:formula_100
where

:formula_101

which must be greater than zero for formula_102 to be evaluated. This may be arranged by permuting x, y and z so that the value of y is between that of x and z.

