<doc id="407039" wikidata="Q2007878" url="?curid=407039" title="Functor category">
<text>In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a functor category formula_1 is a category where the objects are the functors formula_2 and the morphisms are natural transformations formula_3 between the functors (here, formula_4 is another object in the category). Functor categories are of interest for two main reasons: 
* many commonly occurring categories are (disguised) functor categories, so any statement proved for general functor categories is widely applicable;
* every category embeds in a functor category (via the Yoneda embedding); the functor category often has nicer properties than the original category, allowing certain operations that were not available in the original setting.

== Definition ==
Suppose formula_5 is a small category (i.e. the objects and morphisms form a set rather than a proper class) and formula_6 is an arbitrary category. 
The category of functors from formula_5 to formula_6, written as Fun(formula_5, formula_6), Funct(formula_5,formula_6), formula_13, or formula_14, has as objects the covariant functors from formula_5 to formula_6, 
and as morphisms the natural transformations between such functors. Note that natural transformations can be composed: 
if formula_17 is a natural transformation from the functor formula_18 to the functor formula_19, and 
formula_20 is a natural transformation from the functor formula_21 to the functor formula_22, then the composition formula_23 defines a natural transformation 
from formula_24 to formula_22. With this composition of natural transformations (known as vertical composition, see natural transformation), 
formula_1 satisfies the axioms of a category.

In a completely analogous way, one can also consider the category of all &quot;contravariant&quot; functors from formula_5 to formula_6; we write this as Funct(formula_29).

If formula_5 and formula_6 are both preadditive categories (i.e. their morphism sets are abelian groups and the composition of morphisms is bilinear), 
then we can consider the category of all additive functors from formula_5 to formula_6, denoted by Add(formula_5,formula_6).

== Examples ==
* If formula_36 is a small discrete category (i.e. its only morphisms are the identity morphisms), then a functor from formula_36 to formula_5 essentially consists of a family of objects of formula_5, indexed by formula_36; the functor category formula_41 can be identified with the corresponding product category: its elements are families of objects in formula_5 and its morphisms are families of morphisms in formula_5.

* An arrow category formula_44 (whose objects are the morphisms of formula_45, and whose morphisms are commuting squares in formula_45) is just formula_47, where 2 is the category with two objects and their identity morphisms as well as an arrow from one object to the other (but not another arrow back the other way).
* A directed graph consists of a set of arrows and a set of vertices, and two functions from the arrow set to the vertex set, specifying each arrow&#x27;s start and end vertex. The category of all directed graphs is thus nothing but the functor category formula_48, where formula_5 is the category with two objects connected by two parallel morphisms (source and target), and Set denotes the category of sets.
* Any group formula_21 can be considered as a one-object category in which every morphism is invertible. The category of all formula_21-sets is the same as the functor category Setformula_21. Natural transformations are formula_21-maps.
* Similar to the previous example, the category of &quot;K&quot;-linear representations of the group formula_21 is the same as the functor category Vect&quot;K&quot;formula_21 (where Vect&quot;K&quot; denotes the category of all vector spaces over the field &quot;K&quot;).
* Any ring formula_56 can be considered as a one-object preadditive category; the category of left modules over formula_56 is the same as the additive functor category Add(formula_56,formula_59) (where formula_59 denotes the category of abelian groups), and the category of right formula_56-modules is Add(formula_62,formula_59). Because of this example, for any preadditive category formula_5, the category Add(formula_5,formula_59) is sometimes called the &quot;category of left modules over formula_5&quot; and Add(formula_68,formula_59) is the &quot;category of right modules over formula_5&quot;.
* The category of presheaves on a topological space formula_71 is a functor category: we turn the topological space into a category formula_5 having the open sets in formula_71 as objects and a single morphism from formula_74 to formula_75 if and only if formula_74 is contained in formula_75. The category of presheaves of sets (abelian groups, rings) on formula_71 is then the same as the category of contravariant functors from formula_5 to formula_80 (or formula_59 or formula_82). Because of this example, the category Funct(formula_68, formula_80) is sometimes called the &quot;category of presheaves of sets on formula_5&quot; even for general categories formula_5 not arising from a topological space. To define sheaves on a general category formula_5, one needs more structure: a Grothendieck topology on formula_5. (Some authors refer to categories that are equivalent to formula_48 as &quot;presheaf categories&quot;.)

== Facts ==
Most constructions that can be carried out in formula_6 can also be carried out in formula_1 by performing them &quot;componentwise&quot;, separately for 
each object in formula_5. For instance, if any two objects formula_71 and formula_94 in formula_6 have a product formula_96, 
then any two functors formula_24 and formula_21 in formula_1 have a product formula_100, defined by formula_101 
for every object formula_102 in formula_5. Similarly, if formula_104 is a natural transformation and each formula_105 has a kernel formula_106 in the category formula_6, 
then the kernel of formula_108 in the functor category formula_1 is the functor formula_110 with formula_111 for every object formula_102 in formula_5.

As a consequence we have the general rule of thumb that the functor category formula_1 shares most of the &quot;nice&quot; properties of formula_6:
* if formula_6 is complete (or cocomplete), then so is formula_1;
* if formula_6 is an abelian category, then so is formula_1;

We also have:
* if formula_5 is any small category, then the category formula_48 of presheaves is a topos.

So from the above examples, we can conclude right away that the categories of directed graphs, formula_21-sets and presheaves on a topological space are all complete and cocomplete topoi, and that the categories of representations of formula_21, modules over the ring formula_56, 
and presheaves of abelian groups on a topological space formula_71 are all abelian, complete and cocomplete.

The embedding of the category formula_5 in a functor category that was mentioned earlier uses the Yoneda lemma as its main tool. For every object formula_71 of formula_5, 
let formula_129 be the contravariant representable functor from formula_5 to formula_80. The Yoneda lemma states that the assignment 
:formula_132
is a full embedding of the category formula_5 into the category Funct(formula_68,formula_80). So formula_5 naturally sits inside a topos.

The same can be carried out for any preadditive category formula_5: Yoneda then yields a full embedding of formula_5 into the functor category Add(formula_68,formula_59). 
So formula_5 naturally sits inside an abelian category.

The intuition mentioned above (that constructions that can be carried out in formula_6 can be &quot;lifted&quot; to formula_1) can be made precise in several ways; the most succinct formulation uses the language of adjoint functors. 
Every functor formula_144 induces a functor formula_145 (by composition with formula_24). If formula_24 and formula_21 is a pair of adjoint functors, then formula_149 and formula_150 is also a pair of adjoint functors.

The functor category formula_1 has all the formal properties of an exponential object; in particular the functors from formula_152 
stand in a natural one-to-one correspondence with the functors from formula_153 to formula_1. The category formula_155 of all small categories with functors as morphisms 
is therefore a cartesian closed category.

